FROM two_factor_auth
WHERE auth_expiration > CURRENT_TIMESTAMP;

external_knowledge:
- "Total login attempts" refers to the number of times a user tried to log in, regardless of success;
- "Successful login attempts" refers to the number of times a user successfully logged in;
- "Average login time" is the average time at which a user logged in, calculated in Julian days from the Unix epoch (1970-01-01);
- "Most common user agent" is the browser most frequently used by the user;
- "Number of roles" is the count of roles assigned to the user.

- 'admin' is a role with higher privileges in the system;
- 'multiple roles' implies the user has been assigned more than one role;
- 'last recorded login time' refers to the latest time the user logged in before the current activity log entry.

- A login success rate greater than 0.5 means more than half of the login attempts were successful.;
- The halfway mark is analogous to a 50-50 chance, like a coin flip landing heads more than tails.;
- User engagement and system usability can be inferred from login success rates.
